00:00:02.330 --> 00:00:08.929
Professor Ben Polak: All
right, so last time we started

00:00:08.929 --> 00:00:15.475
to study imperfect competition.
We looked at the Cournot model,

00:00:15.475 --> 00:00:20.563
but the bigger theme is the
study of how firms compete

00:00:20.563 --> 00:00:25.842
outside of the sort of easy
cases that you study in 115:

00:00:25.842 --> 00:00:29.970
so outside of the example of
monopoly,

00:00:29.970 --> 00:00:32.159
where there is only one firm
and so there's not much

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:34.691
competition;
and outside the case of perfect

00:00:34.691 --> 00:00:38.553
competition where there are so
many firms, it's as if each firm

00:00:38.553 --> 00:00:41.406
is a price taker.
We're going to continue with

00:00:41.406 --> 00:00:44.734
that today, and in fact you're
going to continue with it on

00:00:44.734 --> 00:00:47.009
into the homework.
So last time,

00:00:47.009 --> 00:00:51.601
we looked at Cournot.
It was the model we started

00:00:51.601 --> 00:00:53.722
with.
We looked at two firms

00:00:53.722 --> 00:00:57.095
competing in quantities.
And just to review a little bit

00:00:57.095 --> 00:00:59.889
what we did last time,
the kind of exercise there--so

00:00:59.889 --> 00:01:01.033
I think,
is this right,

00:01:01.033 --> 00:01:02.890
I think probably went a little
fast last time.

00:01:02.890 --> 00:01:05.938
I was kicking myself afterwards.
People can nod or shake their

00:01:05.938 --> 00:01:07.738
heads.
I think I went a bit fast,

00:01:07.738 --> 00:01:10.514
so I'm sorry for that.
If there was a time to go too

00:01:10.514 --> 00:01:13.554
fast it was probably last time,
because it turns out this is

00:01:13.554 --> 00:01:16.079
something that's covered well in
the textbook,

00:01:16.079 --> 00:01:18.599
so it's covered in chapter six
of the textbook.

00:01:18.599 --> 00:01:22.613
But the kind of exercise we did
last time is a useful exercise

00:01:22.613 --> 00:01:25.180
for those of you who are Econ
majors.

00:01:25.180 --> 00:01:28.866
The way we solved that Cournot
model was we did three kinds of

00:01:28.866 --> 00:01:31.215
things.
We did something very nerdy,

00:01:31.215 --> 00:01:34.440
namely, we just played with
calculus and algebra.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:37.722
That was sort of mathy.
We did something a little bit

00:01:37.722 --> 00:01:40.152
less nerdy, that is,
we drew some pictures that

00:01:40.152 --> 00:01:42.992
represented what we'd found.
And we did a third thing,

00:01:42.992 --> 00:01:45.973
which we tried to match this up
to the economic intuition about

00:01:45.973 --> 00:01:47.994
monopoly,
and perfect competition,

00:01:47.994 --> 00:01:49.800
and demand curves,
and so on.

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:52.977
And this exercise of being able
to work in these three different

00:01:52.977 --> 00:01:56.139
modes, economic intuition,
graphs, and kind of nerdy high

00:01:56.139 --> 00:01:59.462
school math is a lot of what we
want to get you used to as

00:01:59.462 --> 00:02:01.953
Economic Majors,
just to be able to translate

00:02:01.953 --> 00:02:04.373
easily between those.
Again, I apologize for going

00:02:04.373 --> 00:02:06.706
too fast but it's still a useful
exercise I think,

00:02:06.706 --> 00:02:08.419
so have a look at it in the
book.

00:02:08.419 --> 00:02:11.228
Now back to the lessons and
away from the nerdiness a

00:02:11.228 --> 00:02:14.413
second, what did we learn?
Well at the end of the day we

00:02:14.413 --> 00:02:17.530
learned that in the Cournot
Equilibrium, things were,

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:21.295
as we perhaps might have
anticipated--things sat

00:02:21.295 --> 00:02:24.340
naturally between the extreme
cases.

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:26.867
So the amount of output
produced by the industry was

00:02:26.867 --> 00:02:29.742
somewhere between the case that
would be under monopoly and

00:02:29.742 --> 00:02:32.326
under perfect competition.
It was more than under

00:02:32.326 --> 00:02:34.370
monopoly, less than perfect
competition.

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:37.157
Prices in the industry,
if we'd gone back and checked,

00:02:37.157 --> 00:02:39.483
would sit between.
They would be lower than the

00:02:39.483 --> 00:02:41.439
monopoly prices,
but higher than the perfect

00:02:41.439 --> 00:02:44.135
competitive prices.
Industry profits would be in

00:02:44.135 --> 00:02:45.639
between.
Industry profits would be less

00:02:45.639 --> 00:02:46.722
than monopoly.
They must be less than

00:02:46.722 --> 00:02:48.229
monopoly, since that's the
highest they could ever be.

00:02:48.229 --> 00:02:51.464
And they're higher than perfect
competition, which of course,

00:02:51.464 --> 00:02:54.174
has zero profits in this case.
Consumer surplus,

00:02:54.174 --> 00:02:57.069
the benefits flowing to
consumers lie in between.

00:02:57.069 --> 00:02:59.225
So in fact the model,
in addition to the sort of

00:02:59.225 --> 00:03:01.565
nerdiness of the model,
it ended up with a result we

00:03:01.565 --> 00:03:03.934
kind of believe in.
If you have imperfect

00:03:03.934 --> 00:03:07.563
competition, it's somewhere
between perfect competition and

00:03:07.563 --> 00:03:10.580
no competition.
But, what's the "but"?

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:13.584
The "but" is that there are
other ways we could model

00:03:13.584 --> 00:03:16.358
imperfect competition,
and, as we're going to see

00:03:16.358 --> 00:03:18.669
today, they yield different
answers.

00:03:18.669 --> 00:03:24.939
So the first thing we're going
to do today is look at a

00:03:24.939 --> 00:03:31.092
different form of competition
which is called Bertrand

00:03:31.092 --> 00:03:38.531
competition.
The Cournot was competing in

00:03:38.531 --> 00:03:48.099
quantities and Bertrand is
competing in prices.

00:03:48.099 --> 00:03:50.288
Just a quick check and this is
not for the camera,

00:03:50.288 --> 00:03:52.790
how many of you have seen
Bertrand competition before?

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:54.839
So, a good many of you.
So this is going to be review

00:03:54.839 --> 00:03:57.452
still again, and for those of
you for whom it isn't review

00:03:57.452 --> 00:04:00.243
don't worry.
We'll do this relatively

00:04:00.243 --> 00:04:05.240
quickly but I hope I won't rush
it like I did last time.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:07.205
If it's any consolation,
when I feel I've rushed a

00:04:07.205 --> 00:04:08.650
lecture, I have a sleepless
night.

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:12.666
So if you had a sleepless night
because you're worried about it,

00:04:12.666 --> 00:04:15.599
I'm having a sleepless night
too about that.

00:04:15.599 --> 00:04:18.885
So there's two firms,
just as there was before,

00:04:18.885 --> 00:04:22.670
and just as there was
before--so the players are those

00:04:22.670 --> 00:04:27.129
two firms,
and just as there was last

00:04:27.129 --> 00:04:33.250
time, they're producing an
identical product.

00:04:33.250 --> 00:04:36.909
So the products we mentioned
last time were Coke and Pepsi,

00:04:36.909 --> 00:04:40.506
but you could think of other
products that are pretty much

00:04:40.506 --> 00:04:44.524
identical.
Just as last time,

00:04:44.524 --> 00:04:53.752
we're going to assume that
costs are constant marginal

00:04:53.752 --> 00:04:56.343
costs.
We'll assume that constant

00:04:56.343 --> 00:04:58.470
marginal cost just as it was
last time is equal to C.

00:04:58.470 --> 00:05:01.623
Just to remind those people who
are not Economics Majors what

00:05:01.623 --> 00:05:04.566
that means, it means if I
produce 1 unit then it costs me

00:05:04.566 --> 00:05:08.146
C to produce,
if I produce two units it costs

00:05:08.146 --> 00:05:11.180
me 2C, 100 units a 100C and so
on.

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:13.360
Now what's different here from
last time?

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:15.149
I've already told you but I'll
repeat it.

00:05:15.149 --> 00:05:17.751
This time, however,
instead of setting quantities,

00:05:17.751 --> 00:05:20.831
instead of just deciding how
much Coke and Pepsi to produce

00:05:20.831 --> 00:05:24.177
and spewing it out in the market
and letting prices take care of

00:05:24.177 --> 00:05:27.353
themselves,
this time the firms are going

00:05:27.353 --> 00:05:31.899
to set prices and let quantities
take care of themselves.

00:05:31.899 --> 00:05:40.149
So the strategy sets this time
are prices.

00:05:40.149 --> 00:05:43.643
Again, so as we don't get
confused, normally we use S for

00:05:43.643 --> 00:05:46.699
strategy, but let's use P since
they're prices.

00:05:46.699 --> 00:05:51.347
So they're going to P1,
will the price of Firm 1,

00:05:51.347 --> 00:05:54.930
and P2 will be the price of
Firm 2.

00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:59.045
This strategy set--formally,
let's just simplify it

00:05:59.045 --> 00:06:04.230
here--let's assume that for each
Firm i they can set their price

00:06:04.230 --> 00:06:08.510
anything bigger than 0 and
anything less than 1,

00:06:08.510 --> 00:06:13.595
just to keep life simple.
So this is a little bit more

00:06:13.595 --> 00:06:16.974
realistic perhaps.
Perhaps more realistic to think

00:06:16.974 --> 00:06:20.865
of firms actually thinking about
what prices to set and then

00:06:20.865 --> 00:06:25.019
adjusting the quantities they
actually ship based on demand.

00:06:25.019 --> 00:06:27.388
Depends on--I don't want to be
too rigorous about that because

00:06:27.388 --> 00:06:28.980
you could imagine the other way
around,

00:06:28.980 --> 00:06:33.585
but if you talk to managers
this sounds more realistic,

00:06:33.585 --> 00:06:37.680
at least for retail goods like
Coke and Pepsi.

00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:41.343
So we know how prices are set,
they're set by the firms,

00:06:41.343 --> 00:06:45.339
so the next question is where
do the quantities come from?

00:06:45.339 --> 00:06:46.709
So how do--where do the
quantities from?

00:06:46.709 --> 00:06:48.269
And they're going to come from
demand.

00:06:48.269 --> 00:06:53.312
And let me use a big Q(P) to be
the total quantity

00:06:53.312 --> 00:06:59.589
produced--sorry--the total
quantity demanded in the market.

00:06:59.589 --> 00:07:04.487
So this will be total quantity
of goods produced by Firm 1 and

00:07:04.487 --> 00:07:08.100
goods produced by Firm 2 that
are consumed.

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:11.259
So this is the total quantity
of Coke plus Pepsi.

00:07:11.259 --> 00:07:14.292
Now we're going to--notice
there's no subscript on this P

00:07:14.292 --> 00:07:18.178
and you'll see why in a second.
So we'll assume just to make

00:07:18.178 --> 00:07:22.750
life simple, that the total
quantity produced is 1 –P.

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:26.563
And I'll say this and then
write it more carefully,

00:07:26.563 --> 00:07:29.689
where P is the lower of the two
prices.

00:07:29.689 --> 00:07:35.319
So total quantity demand is 1
-P where P is the lower of the

00:07:35.319 --> 00:07:37.533
two prices.
Now to make that

00:07:37.533 --> 00:07:41.064
lower-of-the-two-prices comment
a little bit more rigorous,

00:07:41.064 --> 00:07:44.290
let's figure out what the
demand actually is for these

00:07:44.290 --> 00:07:49.300
firms.
So what's going on here?

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:55.453
So let's look at the demand for
Firm 1, which is going to end up

00:07:55.453 --> 00:07:58.970
being the quantity that they
sell.

00:07:58.970 --> 00:08:03.800
So that's going to be Q1 and
what's that going to be?

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:08.910
Well it's going to 1 -P1 if
they're the low price firm.

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:13.053
So if P1 is less than P2--so if
they're the low price firm--if

00:08:13.053 --> 00:08:17.129
Coke is the low price firm,
only Coke sells in the market.

00:08:17.129 --> 00:08:22.413
There's no Pepsi in the market
and 1 -P1 quantity of Coke is

00:08:22.413 --> 00:08:27.391
sold.
It's going to be 0 if P1 is

00:08:27.391 --> 00:08:32.333
bigger than P2.
So if Pepsi is the low price

00:08:32.333 --> 00:08:36.470
drink in the market then no Coke
is sold at all.

00:08:36.470 --> 00:08:44.809
It's going to be (1 -P1)/2 in
the case where Coke and Pepsi

00:08:44.809 --> 00:08:49.555
cost exactly the same.
These should really be--realize

00:08:49.555 --> 00:08:51.059
that this is not exactly
realistic.

00:08:51.059 --> 00:08:53.473
We're making a lot of very
strong assumptions here,

00:08:53.473 --> 00:08:55.789
but nevertheless,
it's going to be instructive to

00:08:55.789 --> 00:08:57.864
look at this model.
So we've got the firms,

00:08:57.864 --> 00:08:59.876
they're the players,
I know what their strategies

00:08:59.876 --> 00:09:01.852
are,
I know a little bit about the

00:09:01.852 --> 00:09:04.869
structure of the market,
and I still need to tell you

00:09:04.869 --> 00:09:07.996
what payoffs are.
And just as last time the firms

00:09:07.996 --> 00:09:10.470
are going to try and maximize
profits.

00:09:10.470 --> 00:09:12.320
So what's the profit for Firm 1
going to be?

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:15.958
I won't bother to write it
separately for Firm 2,

00:09:15.958 --> 00:09:20.582
it's going to be the quantity
it sells times the price it gets

00:09:20.582 --> 00:09:24.728
for that quantity,
minus that quantity it sells

00:09:24.728 --> 00:09:29.419
times the cost it incurs in
producing that quantity.

00:09:29.419 --> 00:09:35.438
So again, for Firm 1 it's the
quantity it sells times the

00:09:35.438 --> 00:09:41.241
price, this is its revenue,
minus the quantity it sells

00:09:41.241 --> 00:09:45.539
times C, the cost,
this is his cost.

00:09:45.539 --> 00:09:55.340
I can rewrite that a little bit
more simply as Q1[P1 -C].

00:09:55.340 --> 00:10:01.132
Where Q1, let's keep it in
square brackets,

00:10:01.132 --> 00:10:06.578
this Q1 is this object here.
Does everyone understand what's

00:10:06.578 --> 00:10:07.981
going on?
I mean the algebra doesn't

00:10:07.981 --> 00:10:10.046
really help the intuition here.
The intuition is pretty

00:10:10.046 --> 00:10:11.967
straightforward.
Coke and Pepsi are producing

00:10:11.967 --> 00:10:13.870
this stuff.
They're setting prices.

00:10:13.870 --> 00:10:17.970
If Pepsi is the low price then
Coke sells nothing.

00:10:17.970 --> 00:10:21.053
If Coke is the low price it
sells this amount and its

00:10:21.053 --> 00:10:23.840
profits are basically given by
this equation.

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:28.289
It's basically just revenues
minus costs.

00:10:28.289 --> 00:10:31.502
So what we want to do is we
want to figure out what the Nash

00:10:31.502 --> 00:10:33.679
Equilibrium looks like in this
market.

00:10:33.679 --> 00:10:37.604
Just before we go any further,
notice that really this is the

00:10:37.604 --> 00:10:40.220
same basic market we looked at
before.

00:10:40.220 --> 00:10:43.000
Both times there's a demand
curve out there.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.451
In one model we thought of the
firms setting quantities and the

00:10:46.451 --> 00:10:49.388
market determining prices,
and here we have the firms

00:10:49.388 --> 00:10:52.250
setting prices and the market
determining quantities,

00:10:52.250 --> 00:10:57.535
but the basic underlying
economic structure of this is

00:10:57.535 --> 00:11:01.432
very, very similar.
So to find the Nash Equilibrium

00:11:01.432 --> 00:11:03.990
we're going to have to find best
responses.

00:11:03.990 --> 00:11:08.394
So what we're going to do
together is to figure out what

00:11:08.394 --> 00:11:13.120
these best responses look like
and let's try and do that.

00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:17.313
So I want to figure out the
best response of Firm 1 as a

00:11:17.313 --> 00:11:20.440
function of the price chosen by
Firm 2.

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:25.203
Best price for Firm 1 to choose
given that Firm 2 is choosing

00:11:25.203 --> 00:11:27.583
P2.
I want to do this carefully and

00:11:27.583 --> 00:11:31.357
slowly, and before I even start,
let me point out in passing

00:11:31.357 --> 00:11:34.299
that calculus is not going to
help us here.

00:11:34.299 --> 00:11:36.555
So for those of you who are
nerdy enough to understand the

00:11:36.555 --> 00:11:37.940
next sentence let me just say
it.

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:42.441
This is a discontinuous payoff
function, so differentiating

00:11:42.441 --> 00:11:46.058
isn't going to get you very far.
For people whom that didn't

00:11:46.058 --> 00:11:47.289
mean anything,
it doesn't matter.

00:11:47.289 --> 00:11:51.210
We're not going to calculus
today.

00:11:51.210 --> 00:11:54.019
Okay, so there were different
cases to think about.

00:11:54.019 --> 00:11:59.891
So one case to think about is
what if the other firm,

00:11:59.891 --> 00:12:04.633
you're Coke,
what if Pepsi is pricing below

00:12:04.633 --> 00:12:06.508
cost?
You're Coke,

00:12:06.508 --> 00:12:10.583
what should you price as if
you're trying to maximize your

00:12:10.583 --> 00:12:12.461
profits?
Somebody try and wave their

00:12:12.461 --> 00:12:14.159
hands in the air if they know
the answer.

00:12:14.159 --> 00:12:18.409
Pepsi's pricing below cost,
what's your best response?

00:12:18.409 --> 00:12:21.710
The guy in there,
do you want to shout out?

00:12:21.710 --> 00:12:23.542
Student: Just get out of
the market because it's not

00:12:23.542 --> 00:12:24.679
worth it for you to sell
anything.

00:12:24.679 --> 00:12:26.463
Professor Ben Polak:
Right, I've forgotten your name,

00:12:26.463 --> 00:12:28.250
I should know it by now.
Your name is?

00:12:28.250 --> 00:12:30.080
Student: Sudipta.
Professor Ben Polak:

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:31.279
Sudipta says get out of the
market.

00:12:31.279 --> 00:12:34.113
If the other guy is pricing
below costs, you don't want to

00:12:34.113 --> 00:12:36.299
sell anything,
that's the right intuition.

00:12:36.299 --> 00:12:40.519
How in this game do I "get out
of the market?"

00:12:40.519 --> 00:12:42.785
You're absolutely right,
I don't want to be involved in

00:12:42.785 --> 00:12:45.009
this market if the other guy is
selling below cost.

00:12:45.009 --> 00:12:46.980
How do I operationalize that in
this game?

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:50.413
How do I actually manage?
Ale is there somebody here,

00:12:50.413 --> 00:12:53.759
just wait for the mike a second
and now shout it out.

00:12:53.759 --> 00:12:55.875
Student: You could set
your price above his price and

00:12:55.875 --> 00:12:57.667
then no one will buy.
Professor Ben Polak: The

00:12:57.667 --> 00:12:59.009
answer was set your price above
his price.

00:12:59.009 --> 00:13:03.572
So the other guy is pricing
below costs, the way which I

00:13:03.572 --> 00:13:08.299
avoid making losses is to set my
price above his price.

00:13:08.299 --> 00:13:10.940
Let's just make sure we
understand this,

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:14.798
if the other guy is selling
below cost, the only way I can

00:13:14.798 --> 00:13:17.980
make any sales is to price below
his price.

00:13:17.980 --> 00:13:22.167
I will then make sales but each
of those sales I'm making a loss

00:13:22.167 --> 00:13:23.983
on.
I don't want to make losses,

00:13:23.983 --> 00:13:26.951
so I just "get out of the
market," and the way I "get out

00:13:26.951 --> 00:13:29.760
of the market," is by pricing
above the other guy.

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:34.477
Everyone understand that?
Okay, so now more

00:13:34.477 --> 00:13:39.343
interestingly,
we leave a little gap here,

00:13:39.343 --> 00:13:45.039
what if the other guy is
pricing above costs?

00:13:45.039 --> 00:13:46.838
What do I want to do if the
other guy is pricing above

00:13:46.838 --> 00:13:49.355
costs?
Can I get the guy with the

00:13:49.355 --> 00:13:54.019
beard here, shout it out.
Student: You set price

00:13:54.019 --> 00:13:57.190
below his but above or equal to
cost.

00:13:57.190 --> 00:14:00.109
Professor Ben Polak: All
right, so if the other guy is

00:14:00.109 --> 00:14:03.413
pricing above costs,
I want to set prices below his

00:14:03.413 --> 00:14:08.179
so that I steal the whole of the
