That's amazing,

00:29:59.597 --> 00:30:05.250
that stuff's--oh never mind.
Okay but you're making my point.

00:30:05.250 --> 00:30:11.769
The point I'm trying to make
is, products are not identical.

00:30:11.769 --> 00:30:14.392
For the most part there's a
little bit of difference between

00:30:14.392 --> 00:30:16.569
products and that's actually
going to--that is,

00:30:16.569 --> 00:30:19.458
if we inject that little bit of
realism into the world--it's

00:30:19.458 --> 00:30:21.903
actually going to help us.
So what we would like,

00:30:21.903 --> 00:30:24.772
what would we like?
We would like a model in which

00:30:24.772 --> 00:30:28.747
firms set prices because for the
most part we think firms do set

00:30:28.747 --> 00:30:31.839
prices not quantities:
not always but for the most

00:30:31.839 --> 00:30:34.165
part.
But we'd like a model that

00:30:34.165 --> 00:30:37.555
yields an outcome that
looks--that when you only have

00:30:37.555 --> 00:30:41.011
two firms looks somewhere
between monopoly and perfect

00:30:41.011 --> 00:30:43.611
competition.
So we'd like an outcome that

00:30:43.611 --> 00:30:46.913
looks a little bit like Cournot,
but we'd like the strategy set

00:30:46.913 --> 00:30:49.044
to be prices,
and this is going to do the

00:30:49.044 --> 00:30:50.734
trick.
This is going to turn out to do

00:30:50.734 --> 00:30:52.799
the trick as you'll find out in
your homework assignment.

00:30:52.799 --> 00:30:55.190
So how are we going to model
this on the homework?

00:30:55.190 --> 00:30:58.354
The way we're going to model
differentiated products is to

00:30:58.354 --> 00:31:00.630
imagine, just to take a simple
example,

00:31:00.630 --> 00:31:05.385
imagine a city and this city
has one long straight road

00:31:05.385 --> 00:31:08.369
through it.
So this city is not a city in

00:31:08.369 --> 00:31:12.365
New England, it's a city in the
Midwest, where everything's flat

00:31:12.365 --> 00:31:15.220
and the roads just go completely
straight.

00:31:15.220 --> 00:31:17.049
You can think of this as being
a mile long.

00:31:17.049 --> 00:31:20.993
It doesn't really matter,
let's just think of it as being

00:31:20.993 --> 00:31:25.030
a mile long.
We're going to assume that

00:31:25.030 --> 00:31:30.309
consumers are evenly spread
along this city.

00:31:30.309 --> 00:31:33.824
So there's basically consumers
everywhere, they're evenly

00:31:33.824 --> 00:31:37.839
distributed and we're going to
assume that one of these firms,

00:31:37.839 --> 00:31:47.020
let's call it Firm 1 sits at
point 0 and the other firm,

00:31:47.020 --> 00:31:52.338
Firm 2, sits at point 1.
Now, this is what you're going

00:31:52.338 --> 00:31:54.000
to do in the homework
assignment, but I'm just going

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:55.989
to make the argument that you
could also imagine firms sitting

00:31:55.989 --> 00:31:58.806
somewhere between 0 and 1.
We could do a more general job

00:31:58.806 --> 00:32:00.492
if we wanted to,
but for now,

00:32:00.492 --> 00:32:04.226
let's assume that one of these
firms has its shop at one end of

00:32:04.226 --> 00:32:07.654
the town,
and the other one has its shop

00:32:07.654 --> 00:32:12.255
at the other end of the town.
So let's think about a

00:32:12.255 --> 00:32:16.561
particular consumer,
so suppose this consumer is

00:32:16.561 --> 00:32:22.759
here, at point Y say.
So notice that this consumer is

00:32:22.759 --> 00:32:30.350
a distance Y away from Firm 1.
So if she consumes from Firm 1

00:32:30.350 --> 00:32:36.921
she has to walk a distance of Y.
She's a distance of 1 -Y from

00:32:36.921 --> 00:32:43.667
Firm 2, is that right?
So if she consumes from Firm 2

00:32:43.667 --> 00:32:48.774
she has to walk 1 -Y.
That's going to turn out to be

00:32:48.774 --> 00:32:51.190
key in our model as we'll see in
a second.

00:32:51.190 --> 00:32:59.119
So firms, as before,
are going to set prices.

00:32:59.119 --> 00:33:01.236
I won't write everything down
because it's all written down on

00:33:01.236 --> 00:33:03.109
the homework assignment which is
already on the web,

00:33:03.109 --> 00:33:05.309
but in fact firms are going to
maximize profits,

00:33:05.309 --> 00:33:07.509
aim to maximize profits,
firms are going to have

00:33:07.509 --> 00:33:10.113
constant marginal costs.
We'll make one other assumption

00:33:10.113 --> 00:33:14.434
to keep life simple.
We'll assume that each consumer

00:33:14.434 --> 00:33:20.113
buys one and only one product.
Each consumer is going to buy

00:33:20.113 --> 00:33:23.809
one product, either from Firm 1
or from Firm 2.

00:33:23.809 --> 00:33:28.898
So the issue is going to be
which firm does each consumer go

00:33:28.898 --> 00:33:33.187
and buy their product from.
Which firm does each consumer

00:33:33.187 --> 00:33:40.786
choose?
We'll assume that each consumer

00:33:40.786 --> 00:33:52.478
chooses the product whose,
and I'll be careful here,

00:33:52.478 --> 00:34:01.190
whose total cost to her is
smaller.

00:34:01.190 --> 00:34:05.700
What do we mean by total cost?
Well let's look at the consumer

00:34:05.700 --> 00:34:09.379
at point Y.
For example,

00:34:09.379 --> 00:34:21.651
for the consumer at point Y,
if they buy from Firm 1 then

00:34:21.651 --> 00:34:28.782
they pay the price P1,
which is set by Firm 1,

00:34:28.782 --> 00:34:31.799
but they also have to pay a
transport cost,

00:34:31.799 --> 00:34:36.109
the cost to them of having to
walk all the way there and walk

00:34:36.109 --> 00:34:39.568
all the way back.
We'll give a name to that

00:34:39.568 --> 00:34:46.110
transport cost.
We'll say it's TY².

00:34:46.110 --> 00:34:51.843
So Y is the distance they have
to travel and TY²

00:34:51.843 --> 00:34:59.127
is their transport cost.
So this object here we could

00:34:59.127 --> 00:35:08.018
think of as a transport cost.
If the same consumer buys from

00:35:08.018 --> 00:35:15.920
Firm 2 she pays P2 + T times
again the distance squared,

00:35:15.920 --> 00:35:22.541
so that's going to be (1
–Y)²

00:35:22.541 --> 00:35:31.369
and once again this last term
is a transport cost.

00:35:31.369 --> 00:35:34.309
Notice that these transport
costs go up in the distance you

00:35:34.309 --> 00:35:36.540
have to travel and they go up
pretty fast.

00:35:36.540 --> 00:35:42.998
They go up at rates squared.
So what you're going to do on

00:35:42.998 --> 00:35:45.219
the homework assignment is solve
out this market.

00:35:45.219 --> 00:35:48.198
You're going to assume that
firms set prices to maximize

00:35:48.198 --> 00:35:49.867
profits.
You're going to know what

00:35:49.867 --> 00:35:52.365
firm's costs are.
You're going to work out what

00:35:52.365 --> 00:35:55.854
firm's demands are going to look
for each possible price they

00:35:55.854 --> 00:35:58.182
could set.
And you're going to solve out

00:35:58.182 --> 00:36:01.313
the whole Nash Equilibrium.
And then we're going to look at

00:36:01.313 --> 00:36:03.759
that Nash Equilibrium and you're
going to think,

00:36:03.759 --> 00:36:06.725
how does that compare to what I
saw in the Cournot case we

00:36:06.725 --> 00:36:12.633
solved.
So that's on the homework

00:36:12.633 --> 00:36:16.432
assignment.
But before I leave this,

00:36:16.432 --> 00:36:19.537
let me just point out that this
is a little bit more general

00:36:19.537 --> 00:36:23.720
than it might appear.
So here I've treated what makes

00:36:23.720 --> 00:36:29.090
products different as being
where the shops are located.

00:36:29.090 --> 00:36:32.696
So here I've interpreted these
terms here as transport costs,

00:36:32.696 --> 00:36:36.302
and I've interpreted what makes
the products different is the

00:36:36.302 --> 00:36:40.329
fact that one of them is selling
at one of the end of the town,

00:36:40.329 --> 00:36:45.449
and the other one is selling at
the whitehead end of town.

00:36:45.449 --> 00:36:49.131
But actually,
we could consider this model

00:36:49.131 --> 00:36:52.991
more generally,
and let's just do so briefly

00:36:52.991 --> 00:36:55.560
here.
So let me just redraw the town;

00:36:55.560 --> 00:37:01.729
here's my town again.
I don't have to regard this

00:37:01.729 --> 00:37:06.139
product, this line as being
distance along the high street

00:37:06.139 --> 00:37:08.594
of the town.
It could be something else

00:37:08.594 --> 00:37:10.401
about the product.
So, for example,

00:37:10.401 --> 00:37:13.308
in whatever it is you guys
imagine makes Coke and Pepsi

00:37:13.308 --> 00:37:15.300
different, it could be that
thing.

00:37:15.300 --> 00:37:17.429
Don't quite know what that is,
but whatever that is.

00:37:17.429 --> 00:37:19.392
Let me take an example that I
understand better than I

00:37:19.392 --> 00:37:23.989
understand Coke and Pepsi.
So imagine we're talking about

00:37:23.989 --> 00:37:30.159
beer, think about beer,
so this is the beer market.

00:37:30.159 --> 00:37:34.060
This distance here could be
something like the alcohol

00:37:34.060 --> 00:37:36.710
content or the flavor of the
beer.

00:37:36.710 --> 00:37:38.765
You can imagine different
products therefore,

00:37:38.765 --> 00:37:40.914
that are on the market,
positioning themselves,

00:37:40.914 --> 00:37:43.530
or being positioned at
different points on the line.

00:37:43.530 --> 00:37:47.180
So, for example,
up here if you want beer flavor

00:37:47.180 --> 00:37:50.907
this might be Guinness,
which I can't even spell,

00:37:50.907 --> 00:37:54.452
but you know what I mean.
If we think about the drinks

00:37:54.452 --> 00:37:56.900
industry more generally here,
rather than just beer,

00:37:56.900 --> 00:38:01.398
this would be Guinness,
this would be Poland Spring,

00:38:01.398 --> 00:38:06.780
this is water and everything
else would be in between here.

00:38:06.780 --> 00:38:12.602
So if we just go a tiny
distance in here,

00:38:12.602 --> 00:38:18.515
this is Bud Light and so on.
You could put everything on

00:38:18.515 --> 00:38:21.950
this line, I think there may be,
I'm not really allowed to do

00:38:21.950 --> 00:38:25.042
this on this model,
the one thing I can't do is,

00:38:25.042 --> 00:38:28.510
